m in the Arab and Muslim World / rKüntzel, Matthias -- tCHAPTER 10. Disavowal, Distinction, and Repetition: Alain Badiou and the Radical Tradition of Antisemitism / rSeymour, David -- tCHAPTER 11. On the Contemporary Relevance of Arendt's "Jewish Writings" / rFine, Robert -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book springs from the Bristol-Sheffield Hallam Colloquium on Contemporary Antisemitism at the University of Bristol in September 2015. International experts in Religious Studies, Law, Politics, Sociology, Psychology, and History came together to examine the complexities of contemporary antisemitism. Recent attacks on Jews in European cities have increased awareness of antisemitism and, as this collection shows, such attacks cannot be separated from wider geopolitical and ideological factors. One distinct feature of antisemitism today is its demonization of the State of Israel. Older ideas also feature Jews being blamed for all the world's ills, thought to possess almost supernatural levels of power and wealth, and conspiring to harm the non-Jewish other. These and other ideas forming the background to antisemitism in Europe and North America are unpacked in this book with a view to understanding-and thereby combating-contemporary antisemitism. A key concern is how unifying features might be isolated amid the diverse manifestations of this oldest of hatreds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 4a21st century history. 4aAmerican Jews. 4aEuropean Jews. 4aJewish Studies. 4aState of Israel. 4aZionism. 4aanti-Semitism. 4aanti-Zionism. 4aantisemitism. 4aconflict. 4acontemporary antisemitism. 4aholocaust. 4apersecution. 4areligious intolerance. 7aRELIGION / Religious Intolerance, Persecution & 